article.headline: Strom pours in career-high 29 points
article.linkText: Last unbeaten falls: Penn State topples Iowa
article.story:
IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Jess Strom and Penn State saw to it that
Iowa's stint as the nation's only unbeaten team was short.

Strom scored nine of her career-high 29 points in the final 2:18
and Penn State held on after blowing most of a 20-point lead to
beat Iowa (No. 17 ESPN/USA Today; No. 18 AP) 77-71 Thursday night.

Iowa (13-1, 2-1 Big Ten) had been left as the nation's lone
unbeaten Division I team after top-ranked LSU lost at Rutgers on
Wednesday night. But the Hawkeyes couldn't quite make it all the
way back after trailing 59-39 with less than 12 minutes to play.

"A loss is a loss no matter when," Iowa coach Lisa Bluder
said. "It hurts because it's a loss. Not because we were the last
ones in the country, but just because we lost."

Tanisha Wright and Jennifer Harris each scored 18 points for
Penn State (7-6, 2-0), which has played a brutal schedule and
pulled off its third major upset. The Lady Lions also knocked off
then-No. 2 North Carolina and No. 9 Ohio State, both at home.

This victory was just the second in eight road games for Penn
State, which was coming off a 63-51 loss at Marquette.

"We worked real hard for this game and did our homework," Penn
State coach Rene Portland said. "We knew the importance of it, not
just in the Big Ten standings, which is the ultimate for us right
now, but we're a .500 ballclub and we have to be better than a .500
ballclub if we're going to wear a Penn State uniform."

Iowa got 18 points from Johanna Solverson and a huge lift from
reserves Jenee Graham and Morgan Kasperek, with each finishing with
11 points.

With Graham and Kasperek providing the spark, Iowa outscored
Penn State 10-3 to cut the lead to 62-49. Solverson's 3-pointer
capped a 13-0 run that drew the Hawkeyes to 64-62 with 3:50 to play
and they trailed 66-64 after Kasperek's layup with 2:47 remaining.

But Iowa couldn't get the defensive stop it needed to tie or
take the lead and Strom took over down the stretch, scoring on a
driving layup and making seven of eight free throws to keep Penn
State on top.

"They're a good team and good teams are going to make runs and
when that happens, you have to step up, play some defense, get a
stop, score a big basket or whatever it is," Wright said. "They
made their run and we withstood it."

Penn State kept Iowa's leading scorer, the ultra-quick Crystal
Smith, bottled up most of the game. Smith was scoreless in the
first half and finished with nine points, half her average. Iowa
center Jamie Cavey, averaging 15.7 points, scored only six on
3-for-10 shooting.

"We just felt we had to contain a lot of things with Smith,"
Portland said. "We didn't want to get up on her. She's so lighting
fast. She has to be the most improved player in the Big Ten."

Early on, Iowa showed every sign of staying unbeaten. Solverson
scored the game's first eight points and the Hawkeyes were rolling.
But they slowed shortly thereafter and then stalled completely.

An 11-2 run got Penn State back in it and with Iowa making only
one basket in the final 8 minutes of the first half, the Lady Lions
finished the half with a 9-2 run to lead 32-24.

Strom and Harris each hit two 3-pointers in the first 3:10 of
the second half and the lead quickly ballooned to 20. Strom went
5-for-8 from 3-point range and topped her previous best of 24
points against Michigan State in 2003.

Penn State finished with a season-high 10 3-pointers in 21
attempts. The Lady Lions were shooting just 31 percent from beyond
the arc coming in.

"They buried us from 3-point range," Bluder said.
